  "prompt": "How many books does an average person read in a year?",
  "response": "There's no single, definitive answer to how many books the \"average\" person reads in a year. This is because:\n\n*   **\"Average\" can be measured in different ways:** You could calculate the mean (average), median (middle value), or mode (most frequent value), and each could give a different picture.\n\n*   **Reading habits vary widely:** Factors like age, education, income, lifestyle, and access to books all play a role.\n\n*   **Data is limited and often self-reported:** Surveys and studies exist, but they may not be perfectly representative of the entire population. Also people tend to over-estimate on surveys, which is why \"read rate\" is often lower when looking at verified purchasing data.\n\nThat being said, here's a general idea based on available information:\n\n*   **Pew Research Center:** A Pew Research Center study from 2021 found that the average (mean) American adult read **around 12 books per year**. However, the median was only **4 books per year**. This suggests that a smaller group of avid readers significantly skews the average upwards. About 27% of adults read no books in the past year.\n*   **Other Surveys:** Other surveys, such as those conducted by Gallup or specific book retailers, might report slightly different numbers.\n\n**Key Takeaways:**\n\n*   The median is a more accurate representation of the \"typical\" reader.\n*   A significant portion of the population reads very few books per year.\n*   There is a wide range in reading habits, with some people reading dozens of books and others reading none.\n\n**In Conclusion:**\n\nWhile the mean might be around 12 books per year, the median of 4 books is a more realistic expectation of how many books an average person reads in a year.\n",
